			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1318">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Five years ago I left a high-paying position in corporate law and took an 80 percent pay cut to join the staff of the Hunger Project as a full-time fundraiser. I love my work &mdash; which I don&rsquo;t even think of as &ldquo;work&rdquo; but simply as a vehicle for expressing my hopes for the world.</p>

<p>Courtney E. Martin&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4144">The Jar of Coins</a>&rdquo; [March 2008] vividly illustrates the day-to-day questions we face when we try to make a difference: Will my actions be patronizing or counterproductive? Do people need or want my help? How can I &ldquo;empower&rdquo; them to be self-reliant &mdash; and what does that mean, anyway?</p>

<p>None of us has the answers. Still I admire Martin for not only asking the questions but taking the risk of living them.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jim Goodman<br>Philadelphia, Pennsylvania</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1248">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I want to thank Courtney E. Martin [&ldquo;<a href="/article/4144">The Jar of Coins</a>,&rdquo; March 2008] for speaking my heart and surely the hearts of many others in our generation who recognize how much we have been blessed &mdash; with multivitamins and gifted-and-talented programs, yes, but also with the yearning for a better world. We struggle under the weight of our world-saving inclinations, but our struggles are nothing compared to the injustices and hardships that others face.</p>

<p>Here&rsquo;s to continuing to explore those &ldquo;multiple truths&rdquo; Martin writes about. May we be endowed with not just awareness but the courage to act. And may we continue to discover that how we live matters &mdash; to our friends, our communities, and our global neighbors.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Natalie Eisenbarth<br>Washington, D.C.</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

